		<pubDate>Fri, 31 Oct 2014 13:35:04 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=5109#comment-12432</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Well, this seems to be one of those articles, that do more to you than just inspiring and motivating. The best part about the article is that it brings you back to a reality which seems a bit forgotten, but it gives you the tools and makes you realise that no matter what, we all can. 

Well, I am 21. Currently, I am at a position, where I am actually waking up to realize my calling and preparing to go for it. After reading this, I do plan to be consistent and raise the power of my grit, with practice.

There is one question however... Say, a person knows what he or she wants to excel in, but what if a pathological/ inherent need to be heard, appreciated or simply to be known is also tied to it? What if both excellence and fame are priorities? Would concentrating on fame over here, act as a negative catalyst? Would doing that be somewhat similar to focusing on the performance, rather on practice? If yes, then how should a person try to differentiate between the two and work on them individually? If no, then should modifications be made in the tactics mentioned above, to associate them together and work towards the united dream? 

I know, I might be less mature than most of my friends over here...  but, it&#039;s never too early to be clearer about things that matter to an individual.

Thank you.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Well, this seems to be one of those articles, that do more to you than just inspiring and motivating. The best part about the article is that it brings you back to a reality which seems a bit forgotten, but it gives you the tools and makes you realise that no matter what, we all can. </p>
<p>Well, I am 21. Currently, I am at a position, where I am actually waking up to realize my calling and preparing to go for it. After reading this, I do plan to be consistent and raise the power of my grit, with practice.</p>
<p>There is one question however&#8230; Say, a person knows what he or she wants to excel in, but what if a pathological/ inherent need to be heard, appreciated or simply to be known is also tied to it? What if both excellence and fame are priorities? Would concentrating on fame over here, act as a negative catalyst? Would doing that be somewhat similar to focusing on the performance, rather on practice? If yes, then how should a person try to differentiate between the two and work on them individually? If no, then should modifications be made in the tactics mentioned above, to associate them together and work towards the united dream? </p>
<p>I know, I might be less mature than most of my friends over here&#8230;  but, it&#8217;s never too early to be clearer about things that matter to an individual.</p>
<p>Thank you.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
