					<description><![CDATA[Thank you James for another inspiring article. This post came at a right time for me and I finally understand what mental toughness means. 

Thank you for letting me know that it is OK to not be perfect (in everything I do) as long as you persevere in maintaining certain form of small scale habits.

I find it to be similar to your example of eating processed food. When I stop eating processed food for 1 day, I will work harder to ensure that this continues the next day and the day after. Until I achieve a 7 day goal. Will attempt to try that on myself. I have tried so previously, but I haven&#039;t been consistent. 

I have also been working to quit coffee for more than half a year. But of late, I picked up coffee drinking again to test and observe on whether I can still tolerate caffeine. The first time, it was OK. I felt more energized and healthy. And then, the second and third time occurred (weeks later), and it is all back to square one. I am determined to give up coffee for good but I won&#039;t do it so drastically. I am currently switching to tea and hopefully slowly reducing them until it become like &#039;leisure drinking&#039; kind of thing. 

I really hope this kind of small ways in pushing myself for both caffeine drinking and processed food consumption will help me to develop the mental toughness as you described. And also in other areas of my life. 

Will definitely keep reading (or reread) all of your posts to help to motivate myself! :)]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Thank you James for another inspiring article. This post came at a right time for me and I finally understand what mental toughness means. </p>
<p>Thank you for letting me know that it is OK to not be perfect (in everything I do) as long as you persevere in maintaining certain form of small scale habits.</p>
<p>I find it to be similar to your example of eating processed food. When I stop eating processed food for 1 day, I will work harder to ensure that this continues the next day and the day after. Until I achieve a 7 day goal. Will attempt to try that on myself. I have tried so previously, but I haven&#8217;t been consistent. </p>
<p>I have also been working to quit coffee for more than half a year. But of late, I picked up coffee drinking again to test and observe on whether I can still tolerate caffeine. The first time, it was OK. I felt more energized and healthy. And then, the second and third time occurred (weeks later), and it is all back to square one. I am determined to give up coffee for good but I won&#8217;t do it so drastically. I am currently switching to tea and hopefully slowly reducing them until it become like &#8216;leisure drinking&#8217; kind of thing. </p>
<p>I really hope this kind of small ways in pushing myself for both caffeine drinking and processed food consumption will help me to develop the mental toughness as you described. And also in other areas of my life. </p>
<p>Will definitely keep reading (or reread) all of your posts to help to motivate myself! :)</p>
